  "datePublished": "2026-03-04",
  "description": "Aggregation pipelines can amplify bias if they treat iNaturalist data as uniform. Analysis must account for uneven effort and taxonomic detection probability.\n¶Practice guidance Use spatial thinning or bias surfaces when modeling. Track license and geoprivacy constraints during aggregation. Document filtering and exclusion criteria. Retain links to original observation media and comments for auditability. ¶Common aggregation pitfalls Mixing data from different time windows without accounting for effort changes. Treating “Research Grade” as a uniform quality filter across taxa. Dropping coordinate uncertainty fields and then over-interpreting precision. ¶What goes wrong if you do this poorly Aggregated datasets can create false hotspots that reflect observer behavior rather than ecological reality. Without audit trails, errors can become “institutionalized” in derived datasets.\n",
